vegdescription: sclerophyllous forests with evergreen Quercus accompanied by Laurus nobilis. The degradation of these forests corresponds to mattorals where Quercus ilex forests dominate. The Supra-Mediterranean belt is mainly composed of Quercus pubescens associated to Buxus sempervirens. The temperate zone corresponds to deciduous oak mixed forests in plains (< 700 m). The temperate hills and mountains i.e. the northern part of the Alps as well as the Massif Central is characterized by the development of Fagus from 700 to 1000 m high. Fagus is mixed with Abies in higher mountains. Mountainous forests of conifers occur from 1450 to 2500 m high. The Alpine belt begins at ca. 2000-2300 m. The lower part is composed of Ericaceae or alpine grassland with Poaceae, Fabaceae and Cyperaceae

Stony lakeshore in an alpine grassland community of Nardus stricta. Dominance of Nardus stricta, abundance of Rhododendron ferrugineum and presence of Calluna vulgaris, Empetrum nigrum and Trifolium sp.
Grazed open subalpine woodland of Pinus uncinata ssp mugo. Dominance of Juniperus communis ssp alpina, Poaceae and  Pinus uncinata ssp mugo. Presence of Lotus alpinus and Apiaceae.
Intensively grazed fen dominated by Nardus stricta and Cyperaceae. Presence of Asteroideae, Lamium sp, Luzula sp, Ranunculaceae.
Livestock resting place near a rocky slope dominated by Poaceae, Rumex sp and Silene inflata. Presence of Apiaceae, Galium sp, Cichoroideae and Ranunculus acris.
Subalpine dry grazed meadow dominated by Poaceae. Abundance of Galium verum, Plantago minor, Caryophyllaceae and Trifolium sp.
Dense subalpine woodland close to tall grass communities and dominated by Pinus uncinata ssp mugo and  Rhododendron ferrugineum. Also, abundance of Poaceae and Trifolium sp.
Grazed pine forest clearance of c. 800 m dominated by Poaceae. Presence of Pulsatilla montana, Potentilla erecta, Trifolium sp., Calluna vulgaris and Cichoroideae.
Grazed dry meadow on valley floor dominated by Poaceae. Abundance of Galium verum, Achyllea millefolium, Plantago lanceolata and Plantago minor.
Nitrophilous and ruderal community of a livestock enclosure dominated by Poaceae, Chenopodiaceae, Trifolium pratense, Plantago major and Caryophyllaceae.
Grazed pine forest clearance of c. 40x100 m dominated by Poaceae. Abundance of Plantago lanceolata, Caryophyllaceae, Galium verum and Achyllea millefolium.
Grazed mown meadow located near a mountain shelter dominated by Poaceae. Abundance of Plantago media, Chenopodiaceae, Trifolium sp. Presence of Ranunculaceae and Plantago major.
Nitrophilous and ruderal community close to a mountain shelter dominated by Chenopodium bonus-henricus and Urtica dioica. Presence of Poaceae and primulaceae.
Subalpine woodland undergrowth dominated by Arctostaphylos uva-ursi. Abundance of Pinus sylvestris and presence of Betula pendula, Poaceae and Epilobium.
Dense Pinus silvestrys forest without grazing pressure. Abundance of Vaccinium myrtillus and Poaceae and presence of Calluna vulgaris.
Dense Pinus silvestrys woodland close to Abies alba and Betula pendula forest. Dominance of Pinus silvestrys and abundance of Corylus avellana, Abies alba and Poaceae.
Track in pine woodland and Corylus avellana formations. Abundance of Corylus avellana, Buxus sempervirens and Poaceae.
Abandoned cropping terraces colonised by a mountain deciduous forest. Dominance of Pinus sylvestris and abundance of  Poaceae, Quercus petraea, Corylus avellana and Buxus sempervirens
Alpine wet meadows of Nardus stricta. Dominance of Nardus stricta, presence of Lamium sp, Calluna vulgaris, Trifolium sp, Asteroideae, Plantago sp.
Livestock resting place near a lake and a shepherd shed. Dominance of Nardus stricta, abundance of Trifolium repens and Lotus sp. and presence of Asteroideae.
Pine tree limit in south facing slope colonised by Juniperus communis ssp alpina. Abundance of Poaceae, Juniperus communis ssp alpina, and presence of Pinus uncinata ssp mugo and Trifolium repens.

Open subalpine woodland with Juniperus communis ssp alpina undergrowth. Dominance of Pinus uncinata ssp mugo,  Juniperus communis ssp alpina and Poaceae. Presence of Rhododendron ferrugineum, Vaccinium myrtillus and Calluna vulgaris.
Dense subalpine woodland of Pinus uncinata ssp mugo, which dominates de plant assemblage.  Abundance of Rhododendron ferrugineum, Vaccinium myrtillus and Poaceae.

Remnant oak woodland located just below the top of Jebel esh-Shara (1736 m).  Quercus calliprinos woodland with a few Pistacia palestina trees form the overstory with a sparse understory including Astragalus sp., other Papilionaceae, and grasses.  Artemisia herba-alba shrubs grow in disturbed areas.
Hammada salicornia, Fagonia mollis, grasses, Peganum hamala, and Chenopodiaceae with a few Ephedra on rocky cliffs and Centaurea in disturbed areas.

Fagonia mollis, Aellenia lancifolia, grasses, Centaurea, Retama raetam, Ballota undulata, and Limonium thouinii, Acacia sp., Pistacia sp., Retama raetam, Zilla spinosa, Alcea cf. rufescens, and Peganum hamala grow in wadi.
Hammada salicornia, Peganum hamala, Fagonia mollis, and grasses.  Retama raetam, Asteraceae, Zilla spinosa, and Acacia sp. grow along the wadi.
Hammada salicornia, Fagonia mollis, Ballota undulata, Ephedra, grasses, and Zygophyllum dumosum.  Acacia sp., Ziziphus spina-christi, and Retama raetam grow in wadi.
Very sparse vegetation.  A few grasses and Aellenia lancifolia.
Very sparse vegetation.  Grasses, Aellenia lancifolia, Fagonia mollis, and Plantago sp., Hammada salicornia in wadi.
Sparse vegetation on alluvial outwash within Wadi Araba.  Grasses, Aellenia lancifolia, Fagonia mollis, and  Plantago sp.
Grasses, Plantago sp. and Haloxylon persicum.  Acacia sp. grows at edge of dunes.
Hammada salicornia, grasses, and Plantago sp. A few small Acacia trees along drainages.
Sparse vegetation with Plantago sp., grasses, Haloxylon persicum, Hammada salicornia, Centaurea and Neurada procumbens.

Located near the edge of remnant oak stand.  Quercus calliprinos woodland with a single Pistacia palestina tree.  Understory includes Artemisia herba-alba and a few grasses, Peganum harmala grows in disturbed places with Verbascum sp., and Ononis sp.
Sparse vegetation. Plantago sp., grasses, Hammada salicornia and a few Haloxylon persicum.  Acacia sp. grows along drainages.  Calotropis procera trees.
Pine tree limit in north facing slope colonised by Rhododendron ferrugineum, which dominates de plant assemblage. Also abundance of Juniperus communis ssp alpina, Vaccinium myrtillus and Poaceae.

Samples were collected below the Pleistocene shoreline.  Vegetation is much more abundant than in sample # 2.  Tamarix sp., Halyoxylon persicum., Acacia sp.,  Calotropis procera, and grasses are found with Phragmities sp. along wadis.
Shrub steppe domiated by Artemisia herba-alba with grasses, Echinops, and Centaurea. A few scattered Q. calliprinos are found in vicinity.
Degraded Artemisia herba-alba shurb steppe with grasses and cultivated Triticum in nearby fields with Echinops and Centaurea.  A single Crataegus tree grows at edge of field.
Degraded Artemisia herba-alba shrub steppe with grasses, Ephedra sp., and Retama raetam, Echinops, Centaurea., and Ononis in disturbed areas.  Juniperus phoenica grows on rocky outcrops.

Degraded Artemisia herba-alba shrub steppe with grasses, Retama raetam, Ephedra, and Centaurea.  Thymelaea hirsuta grows nearby.  Sample from just above Beidha housing, wheat fields (Triticum), and heavily grazed vegetation characterize the area.

Broad valley with rocky outcrops on either side.  Degraded Artemisia shrub steppe with plowed wheat fields. Juniperus phoenicia., Retama raetam, Ephedra, grasses, Fagonia mollis var. glabratra, Thymelaea hirsuta, Echinops, and Centaurea.

Retama raetam, Artemisia herba-alba, Fagonia mollis var. glabratra, Ephedra,  grasses common with a few Helianthemum cf. stipulatum, Centaurea, and Echinops.  Juniperus phoenica, Pistacia atlantica, and Nerium oleander grow in wadi.
Artemisia herba-alba and Hammada salicornia common.  Ephedra rare.  A few Juniperus phoenica on rocky ourcrops.

Mixed coppice beneath a canopy of mainly Quercus and Betula standards. The coppiced stools consist predominantly of Corylus avellana and Fraxinus excelsior, though unusually Alnus glutinosa is co-dominant over an area of about 40 ha.  Primula elatior, Filipendula ulmaria and Mercurialis perennis are common in the ground flora, with Rubus spp., Pteridium aquilinum and Hyacinthoides non-scriptus also common.

Area of open heath with surrounding softwood and hardwood plantations, including Pinus sylvestris, P. nigra, Pseudotsuga menziesii, Picea abies, Quercus and Fagus sylvestris. Mire vegetation is dominated by a central valley channel dominated by Molinia caerulea, Eriophorum angustifolium, with Myrica gale and Juncus acutiflorus. Margins of the mire compose a large area of step mireconsisting of Sphagnum lawn. Areas are frequently colonised by Ulex europaeus and Pinus sylvestris and encroachment of Pteridium aquilinum

Large valley mire situated within an area of open heathland with surrounding mixed woodland and plantations comprising principally Quercus robur, Q. petraea, Fagus sylvatica and Pinus sylvestris with Larix decidua, Pseudotsuga menziesii, Tsuga heterophylla, Pinus nigra and Picea sitchensis also present. Mire vegetation is dominated by a Sphagnum carpet of S. auriculatum and S. cuspidatum. Molinia caerulea, Eriophorum angustifolium, Juncus acutiflorus, Erica tetralix are abundant, with Rhynchospora alba and Eleocharis multicaulis also frequent in parts of the site

Part of a large valley mire system situated within an area of open heathland with several small stands of Ilex aquifolium, Pinus sylvestris and Betula pendula, with larger deciduous and softwood plantations c. 1km to the south and south west. Coring location was within open tussocky Molinia community with Eriophorum angustifolium abundant. To the south along the axis of drainage Salix carr woodland is present with Carex paniculata, Lysimachia vulgaris, Myrica gale, Glyceria fluitans, Dryopteris austriaca and widespread Sphagnum squarrosum lawn.

Site is set within predominantly open heathland with some Betula pendula scrub, surronded by mixed plantations, natural woodland stands and valley mires. Site vegetation is very wet Sphagnum lawn compossed mainly of S. papilosum and S. recurvum, with some S. cuspidatum, Eriophorum angustifolium, Erica tetralix, Molinia caerulea and scattered Myrica gale.

Large raised bog, predominantly Spagnum lawn with Calluna vulgaris, Erica tertralix and Eriophorum vaginatum the main plant types. Situated within an area of open uplands which is heavily grazed, but patches of mixed woodland and wood fen are found along the northern edge of the mire.
Large upland lake with Malham Tarn Moss making its western boundary. Largely open and heavily grazed landscape with small patches of mixed woodland nearby.

Quercus robur is the main standard species, though other species including Tilia cordata, Carpinus betulus and Castanea sativa are also present as maidens. Coppiced Tilia cordata is abundant with, in some areas, Castanea sativa co-dominant. Small but distinct areas with coppiced Carpinus betulus, Fraxinus excelsior, Acer campestre or Corylus avellana co-dominant as the coppiced species also occur. The ground vegetation is dominated by Hyacinthoides non-scripta with Rubus spp. and Pteridium aquilinum also locally abundant.
Moss from a phrygana with Paliurus spina-christia and Phlomis fruticosa, close to a specimen of  Quercus macrolepis

Mixed coppice beneath a thin canopy of Quercus robur standards. Fraxinus excelsior and Acer campestre generally occur as large stools with relatively few tall regrowths. Corylus avellana forms the bulk of smaller stools and Prunus spinosa and Crataegus monogyna are common as under-storey shrubs. Ground flora dominated by Primula elatior, Filipendula ulmaria, Hyacinthoides non-scriptus and Mercurialis perennis.

sitename: Attika, close to the village Anavyssos
sitedescription: Attika, close to the village Anavyssos
vegdescription: path close to the village Anavyssos

Sample taken within an area of Alnus glutinosa carr woodland. Open areas of the mire to the north are dominated by Juncus acutiflorus over a carpet of Sphagnum recurvum. To the south-west, open areas are dominated by Agrostis canina with Carex paniculata and Carex remota, with patches of Myrica gale abundant. The surrounding dryland is dominated by a mixture of mature ancient woodland comprising a mixture of Quercus sp. and Fagus sylvatica, many of the later having been pollarded. Also common is an understorey of Ilex aquifolium. Adjacent to patches of ancient woodland are more recent plantations comprising Fagus sylvatica, Quercus, Pinus sylvestris and Picea abies. The local area is heavily grazed by cattle, ponies and deer

Large valley mire with well developed Sphagnum lawns, consisting predominantly of S. papilosum with a number of other Sphagna present. Molinia caerulea, Narthecium, Erica tetralix and Eriophorum angustifolium are abundant. Flushing zones along the edge of the mire are dominated by Schoenus nigrcans, with Cirsium dissectum frequent in other areas of the mire. Surrounding dryland is dominated by open dry and wet heathland and extensive shallow valley mire deposits. Close to the mire are stands of Pinus sylvestris. Stands of ancient woodland containing mixed Quercus robur and Fagus sylvatica are located c. 0.5km to the east of the mire.

Sample taken within an area of Alnus glutinosa carr woodland, with adjacent open areas of the mire dominated by Juncus acutiflorus over a carpet of Sphagnum recurvum with patches of Myrica gale abundant. The surrounding dryland is dominated by a mixture of mature ancient woodland comprising a mixture of Quercus sp. and Fagus sylvatica, many of the later having been pollarded. Also common is an understorey of Ilex aquifolium. Adjacent to patches of ancient woodland are more recent plantations comprising Fagus sylvatica, Quercus, Pinus sylvestris and Picea abies. The local area is heavily grazed by cattle, ponies and deer

Area of open heath with surrounding softwood and hardwood plantations, including Pinus sylvestris, P. nigra, Pseudotsuga menziesii, Picea abies, Quercus and Fagus sylvestris. Mire is comprised of a central channel composed mainly of Sphagnum palustra and S. papillosum, with Eriophorum angustifolium and Molinia caerulea abundant along with Erica tetralix and Drosera rotundifolia.

Open Sphagnum lawn, composed principally of Sphagnum recurvum  and S. papillosum, with Molinia caerulea, Narthecium, Erica tetralix, Eleocharis multicaulis and Drosera rotundifolia present. Surrounding dryland is ancient woodland composed principally of mixed Quercus robur and Fagus sylvatica with an understorey of Ilex aquifolium and heavily grazed grass lawns

vegdescription: Ombrotrophic bog, still growing, raised bog species, including Vaccinium oxycoccus and Andromeda polifolia. Dominant elements are Sphagnum magellanicum, S. rubellum, S. angustifolium, Eriophorum angustifolium and E. vaginatum. Small Betula on bog. Area around the maar: ~1.7 ha deciduous forest, ~0.9 ha coniferous forest and relatively little pasture (Forst et al., 1997). Arable land exists beyond the maar crater slopes but not in direct proximity to the bog.

Ombrotrophic bog, not growing, with trees, on bog 1997: Picea abies (20m), Betula pubescens (10m); shrub layer: Sorbus aucuparia, Picea abies, Pinus sylvestris, Frangula alnus; ground vegetation layer includes Vaccinium myrtillus, Dryopteris dilatata, D. carthusiana, Trientalis europaea, Molinia caerulea. Around bog: Pteridium aquilinum with Corydalis claviculata, Galiuim hercynicum. Partition in which bog is located: Pinus, Fagus, Quercus; Rubus ideaus, Oxalis acetosella, Hieracium, seedlings of variety of trees. Partition further south with planted Picea and Larix. Partition further east with planted Pseudotsuga, Picea, Abies.
notes: Samples: First cm from bog surface.

sitename: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
vegdescription: Piceeta nemoraliosa - The forests in this group occur in the upper part of the relief on relatively rich soil. Their most important characteristic is the presence in the tree and shrub layers of broad-leaved species, such as Corylus avellana, Tilia cordata, Ulmus, Fraxinus excelsior). An understorey of Corylus avellana, Lonicera xylosteum and Sorbus aucuparia is usually well developed. In the rather abundant field layer, mesophytic herbs are prominent. The moss cover, unlike the other vegetationtypes, is poorly developed or absent.

sitename: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
vegdescription: Piceeta hylocomiosa - These vegetation types are prevail in plant cover of the CFSNBR. These forests have a dense cover of mosses (30-35%, Pleurozium schreberi, Hylocomium splendens). There is no understorey, but the field layer is well developed. Its structure and species composition are closely correlated with soil conditions. The common species are Oxalis acetosella, Maianthemum bifolium, Vaccinium myrtillus, V. vitis-idaea, Linnaea borealis.

sitename: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
vegdescription: Piceeta uliginoso-herbosa - This group of vegetation types is characteristically connected with Mezha river valley and its tributaries. Forest stands include Picea, Betula, Alnus glutinosa, A. incana, Salix caprea, rare Fraxinus excelsior. An understorey consists of Frangula alnus, Ribes nigrum, Viburnum opulus and often of Corylus avellana The herb layer is dense, high and rich in species (Aconitum septentrionale, Cinna latifolia, Mercurialis perennis, Aihyrium filix-femina, Dryopteris carthusiana, Poa remota, Cirsium oleraceum). In the most favorite habitats broad-leaved trees (Tilia cordata, Ulmus) take part in the forest stands and understorey.

sitename: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
vegdescription: Piceeta sphagnosa - This group is characteristic of poorly drained and rather wet sites with flat relief. The stands are mainly composed of Picea spp. with an admixture of Betula.  The Sphagnum type of spruce forest has usually two layers, the sparse spruce stand and the ground layer of Sphagnum spp. (S. capillifolium, S. centrale, S. magellanicum, S. palustre and S. squarrosum). Among herbs in this type of forest Vaccinium myrtillus is common, and on small mounds Linnaea borealis and V. vitis-idaea.

Among herbs in this type of forest Vaccinium myrtillus is common, and on small mounds Linnaea borealis and V. vitis-idaea.

sitename: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
vegdescription: Piceeta hylocomiosa - These vegetation types are prevail in plant cover of the CFSNBR. These forests have a dense cover of mosses (30-35%, Pleurozium schreberi, Hylocomium splendens). There is no understorey, but the field layer is well developed. Its structure and species composition are closely correlated with soil conditions. The common species are Oxalis acetosella, Maianthemum bifolium, Vaccinium myrtillus, V. vitis-idaea, Linnaea borealis.

sitename: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
vegdescription: Piceeta uliginoso-herbosa - This group of vegetation types is characteristically connected with Mezha river valley and its tributaries. Forest stands include Picea, Betula, Alnus glutinosa, A. incana, Salix caprea, rare Fraxinus excelsior. An understorey consists of Frangula alnus, Ribes nigrum, Viburnum opulus and often of Corylus avellana The herb layer is dense, high and rich in species (Aconitum septentrionale, Cinna latifolia, Mercurialis perennis, Aihyrium filix-femina, Dryopteris carthusiana, Poa remota, Cirsium oleraceum). In the most favorite habitats broad-leaved trees (Tilia cordata, Ulmus) take part in the forest stands and understorey.

sitename: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
vegdescription: Piceeta nemoraliosa - The forests in this group occur in the upper part of the relief on relatively rich soil. Their most important characteristic is the presence in the tree and shrub layers of broad-leaved species, such as Corylus avellana, Tilia cordata, Ulmus, Fraxinus excelsior). An understorey of Corylus avellana, Lonicera xylosteum and Sorbus aucuparia is usually well developed. In the rather abundant field layer, mesophytic herbs are prominent. The moss cover, unlike the other vegetationtypes, is poorly developed or absent.

vegdescription: Relict broad-leaved formations occurred in the lowland (below1500 m), with conifers over 1300 m; spruce (Picea abies (L.) Karsten)-dominated formations with larch (Larix deciduas Miller) developed at 1500-1800 m. Larch-dominated woods (1800 and 2150 m), with shrubs such as Rhododendron ferrugineum L., Vaccinium myrtillus L., Juniperus communis L., and herbs forming the understory above 2000 m. The larches gave place over 2300m to shrub-dominated communities with Salix hastata L. and typical alpine pasture taxa like Trifolium alpinum L., Carex curvula All., Nardus stricta L. and Leontodon pyrenaicus Gouan ssp. helveticus Finch. The upper limit for isolated trees was around 2415 m, and above this alpine pastures became dominant. Above 2500m plant communities were dominated by Poaceae and Cyperaceae and characterised by typical alpine herbaceous taxa (Silene acaulis (L.) Jacq., Trifolium alpinum, Myosotis alpestris gr., Alchemilla vulgaris gr., Gentiana verna L., Leucanthemopsis alpina (L.) Heywood, Viola tricolor L., Sagina sp., Saxifraga sp., Rumex alpinus L., Trifolium pratense L. ssp. Frigidum Gaudin, Artemisia glacialis L.).

vegdescription: Broad-leaved formations with Quercus, Carpinus, Tilia, Castanea (below 1000 m), Fagus woods with Acer, Fraxinus, Corylus (below 1300 m), Picea woods (below 1800 m), open conifer formations with shrubs in the understory (Picea abies, Pinus cembra, Rhododendron ferrugineum, Vaccinium myrtillus) and alder formations (Alnus viridis (Chaix) DC., Rumex arifolius All., Geranium sylvaticum L.) (1800-2000 m), alpine pastures with shrubs (Nardus stricta, Luzula sp., Rhododendron ferrugineum, Vaccinium myrtillus) (2000-2350 m), alpine discontinuous communities (Minuartia sp., Sempervivum arachnoideum L., Silene acaulis) (2350-2600 m).

locationnotes: Point placed according to description and figures in ref. paper (Fig. 2 in ref paper is flipped horizontally). (MZ)
sitedescription: Located in the low-alpine belt, on the terminal moraine that has been dated to c. AD 1750.
vegdescription: Heath community. Dense ericaceous heath, dominated by dwarf shrubs such as Empetrum nigrum, Vaccinium vitis-idaea, V. myrtillus, Phyllodoce caerulea and Betula nana. A variety of late successional herbs are present including Juncus trifidus, Pinguicula vulgaris, Bartsia alpina and Tofieldia pusilla. The vegetation cover is c. 95%.

locationnotes: Point placed according to description and figures in ref. paper (Fig. 2 in ref paper is flipped horizontally). (MZ)
sitedescription: Located on the 1930 moraine in the mid-alpine belt. The site is located close to a large melt-water stream and adjacent to a semi-permanent snow patch.
vegdescription: Salix-shrub community. The vegetation consists of a low dense scrub, dominated by shrub willows such as Salix glauca, S. phylicifolia and S. herbacea. Several herbs are also present including Festuca ovina, Deschampsia alpina, Carex spp. and Oxyria digyna. At this site there is c. 80% vegetation cover.

locationnotes: Point placed according to description and figures in ref. paper (Fig. 2 in ref paper is flipped horizontally). (MZ)
sitedescription: Mid- alpine belt on fluted moraines near the snout of Storbreen. This terrain has been deglaciated since 1951. The till substrate is disturbed by frequent freeze-thaw cycles and the sites are extremely exposed.
vegdescription: Pioneer community. The sparse vegetation, rarely exceeding a cover of 40%, consists of small clumps of moss and herbs such as Saxifraga nivalis, S. cespitosa, Oxyria digyna, Ranun- culus glacialis, Cerastium cerastoides, Phleum alpinum, Deschampsia alpina and Poa alpina.

vegdescription: Heavily grazed meadows in a rural context. Open thickets with Acer pseudoplatanus, Fraxinus excelsior, Tilia cordata, Juglans, Picea abies, Larix decidua.
Mown meadows surrounded by deciduous trees (eg Fraxinus excelsior, Betula alba, Corylus avellana, Larix decidua).
Opening in Abies alba forest with subordinated Larix decidua, Picea abies,  Sorbus aucuparia, Populus tremula, Betula alba.
Molinia coreulea slope mire with open woodland (eg Betula alba, Alnus incana, Acer pseudoplatanus, Larix decidua).
Grazed dry meadows (Nardus stricta) with scattered shrub groves (Juniperus communis, Juniperus nana, Berberis vulgaris) surrounded by Larix and Picea forest.
Shaded small opening in wooded area with Picea abies, Larix decidua and sparse Pinus cembra tree individuals.
Small hollow within dense Picea abies woodland, also including Larix decidua, Acer pseudoplatanus and Salix cf caprea.
Small opening in Picea abies woodland with Sorbus aria tree individuals.
Sunny opening in wooded area (Picea abies, Larix decidua, Pinus cembra, Alnus glutinosa). At ca 100 m distance a lodge surrounded by mown meadows and megaforbs (eg Rumex and Epilobium).
Avalanche rill with scattered Larix decidua and Pinus cembra trees. Grazed dry meadows in the surroundings.
Tall herb megaforb community in Larix decidua and Pinus cembra woodland.
Pinus cembra - Larix decidua open forest with shrubs (eg Ericaceae).
Pinus cembra - Larix decidua open forest.
Mire surrounded by scattered Larix decidua and Pinus cembra tree individuals.
Dry grassland (Agrostis) on the top of a rocky emergence. In the surrounding area: Pinus cembra and Larix decidua trees.
Low-pressure grazed pasture with scattered Larix decidua, Pinus cembra, Alnus viridis. At ca 50 m distance, there is a lodge with ruderal species.
Scree slope with scattered Larix decidua, Pinus cembra and Alnus viridis.
Wet grassland surrounded by scattered Larix decidua, Pinus cembra and Alnus viridis tree individuals.

Cold moorland with Ericaceae heaths (eg Rhododendron ferrugineum, Vaccinium gaultherioides and Vaccinium myrtillus) mixed with dwarf shrubs (eg Salix herbacea and Salix foetida). Scattered trees, the nearest at ca 70 m far is a Pinus cembra tree individual.
Small mire surrounded by dry meadows on rocky slopes (Nardus stricta and Leontodon helveticus). Pinus cembra krummholz on rocky patches.
Small spring with mire plants (eg Carex foetida, Carex fusca). In the surrounding area: alpine meadows (eg Nardus stricta) on the east facing slopes.
Mire surrounded by dry grasslands on steep slopes with scattered shrubs(eg Juniperus nana, Rhododendron ferrugineum, Vaccinium gaultherioides and Vaccinium uliginosum).
Wet meadow (Nardus stricta and Leontodon cf helveticus) surrounded by dwarf scrubs (eg Salix herbacea).
Rocky slope covered by dwarf shrubs (eg Salix herbacea).
Little Ice Age moraine colonized by dry grasslands (eg Achillea moschata, Trifolium badium and isolated patches of Carex curvula).

sitedescription: Coastal area lying on the former Salpi Lagoon in Apulia region
vegdescription: The present landscape of the site is characterized by arable lands mostly cultivated with cereals. This treeless area presents widespread arid pastures rich in Ferula communis, Scolymus hispanicus, Asphodelus spp. and Plantago spp. Sparse olive orchards are present not far from the site. The original lagoonal environment and its brackish vegetation, mostly represented by the genera Salicornia, Sarcocornia, and Salsola of the Amaranthaceae family, are preserved in the close protected wetland of Palude Frattarolo.

sitedescription: Tectonic lake close to the easternmost coast of Italian Peninsula
vegdescription: The present vegetation of the area is highly degraded, and the natural evergreen arboreal cover is very limited. The landscape is now characterized by olive groves, cultivated land and stands of planted Pinus halepensis. In the residual patches of maquis the dominant species is Quercus coccifera, mostly accompanied by Olea europaea var. sylvestris, Pistacia lentiscus, Phillyrea latifolia, Arbutus unedo, Erica manipuliflora, Rhamnus alaternus, Myrtus communis, Ceratonia siliqua, and Calycotome spinosa. The shore of Lago Alimini Piccolo is occupied by lush reeds dominated by Phragmites australis. Lago Alimini Grande presents an abundant halophilic flora, with several species of Plantago and Limonium along its shore.

vegdescription: Open, mixed coniferous forest (Picea-Larix), broad-leaved scrubs (Laburnum, Alnus viridis, Acer pseudoplatanus) and tall herbs (Cicerbita).

Pasture and larch parkland; small groves of mountain dwarf pine (Pinus mugo) and three individuals of stone pine (Pinus cembra). At the plot border there is an isolated wood of stone pine and extensive scrubs formed by mountain dwarf pine.
Mountain alder scrub with thickets of the endemic tall herb Sanguisorba dodecandra.
Mountain alder scrub with rich tall herb vegetation in the understory.

sitedescription: The vegetation is characteristic of the oro-Mediterranean thorn cushion plant formations of the High Atlas (Navarro et al. 2009) consisting of sparse shrubs and a range of perennial herbs and grasses. These include cushion-form spiny sub-shrubs such as Bupleurum spinosum Gouan and members of the Fabaceae family (Erinacea anthyllis Link, Cytisus spp., Astragalus spp.), accompanied by low-growing plants from Crassulaceae, Helianthemum spp. and Lamiaceae (Thymus spp.). Berberis hispanica Boiss. et Reut. and Prunus prostrata Labill. develop in rocky crevices and gullies. There is considerable grazing pressure from sheep and goats. There is little to no tree cover in the immediate area, excluding occasional junipers (Juniperus thurifera) near the lake itself, and a few trees (Pinus halepensis Mill. and Populus sp.) around the western margin of the lake. Tree cover with J. thurifera and Quercus rotundifolia is developed at around 20 km distance across the watershed to the northwest on Atlantic (northwest) facing slopes, and Cedrus forest is located around 40 km distance to the northeast on the slopes of Jbel Masker.

sitedescription: The site lies within the montane-Mediterranean bioclimate, and the dominant arboreal taxa at the site are Cedrus atlantica, Quercus rotundifolia and Juniperus thurifera. The forest cover around Sidi Ali is degraded by commercial logging, cutting for firewood and grazing pressure. The cedar population at Sidi Ali, which includes individuals of > 900 years in age (Copes-Gerbitz, unpublished dendrochronological data), shows signs of extensive senescence and dieback. Restoration efforts including planting of seedlings are underway, but there does not yet appear to be widespread establishment of young trees in the area. The surrounding vegetation is a mix of scrub and forest (Morgan 1982; Lecompte 1986). A wide range of woody taxa can be observed around Sidi Ali, including Ribes uva-crispa L., Rosa spp. and Berberis hispanica along the rocky lake margins, spiny cushion-form shrubs in open areas including Erinacea anthyllis, and a range of mesic tree taxa in the best preserved forest fragments on the north-facing slopes of the lake’s southern margin. These latter include Acer monspessulanum L., Crataegus lacciniata Steven ex Besser and Fraxinus dimorpha Coss. et Dureiu. The lake is a popular tourist spot and the area is subject to extensive animal grazing.

The surrounding vegetation is a mix of scrub and forest (Morgan 1982; Lecompte 1986). A wide range of woody taxa can be observed around Sidi Ali, including Ribes uva-crispa L., Rosa spp. and Berberis hispanica along the rocky lake margins, spiny cushion-form shrubs in open areas including Erinacea anthyllis, and a range of mesic tree taxa in the best preserved forest fragments on the north-facing slopes of the lake’s southern margin. These latter include Acer monspessulanum L., Crataegus lacciniata Steven ex Besser and Fraxinus dimorpha Coss. et Dureiu. The lake is a popular tourist spot and the area is subject to extensive animal grazing.

sitedescription: Michliffen is a popular touristic destination with a small ski resort, but retains a healthy forest cover (Figure 2G–I), as well as a population of the emblematic Barbary macacques (Macaca sylvanus L.). The southernfacing caldera slopes are covered by a montane Mediterranean mixed needle leaf-broadleaf forest with Cedrus atlantica and Quercus rotundifolia, with other taxa including Acer monspessulanum and Juniperus oxycedrus L. The northern-facing slopes are dominated by stands of C. atlantica.

notes: Calcareous soil on rocky substrate with organic leaf litter

locationnotes: Moss polsters samples were collected at each location to provide modern pollen data, with positional and altitudinal data recorded using a portable Juno 3D Trimble Ltd. Global Positioning System (GPS) device (Glais et al., 2016).
notes: Moss samples were collected over an area of approximately 100 m2 by taking multiple moss polsters from the concerned site to ensure an even representation (Glais et al., 2016).

vegdescription: The modern swamp is sedge-sphagnum, meso-eutrophic. In the cover - sphagnum  and green mosses, sedges, shrubs, in the stands - rarely pine and birch. In the surrounding of the lake are pine forests

The swamp is mesotrophic, with a forest stand of pine and birch, in the willow undergrowth. Herbaceous cover: wild rosemary, marsh cinquefoil (Comarum palustre L.), grasses (Calamagrostis langsdorfii (Link.) Trin., Phragmites), marsh horsetail (Equisetum palustre L.), sedges, sphagnum mosses. On the bumps near the trees grows cranberries (Oxycoccus palustris Pers.
notes: Area of site <5

locationnotes: Behind previous site, on second of moraines, just inside the terminal moraine.  15 m from path and 25 m from river.  On summit of moraine.
On 1750 terminal moraine, behind J.A. Matthews C14 pit, on slope facing glacier.  Near summit of moraine.  C 300 m from main river and 270 m from path.
On first large moraine/hill outside the terminal moraine, before the saeters, c. 200 m upslope from river  and 70 m from path, near very large boulder.
On lateral moraine/ridge directly above saeters.  150 m directly above brown saeter near a large boulder.
c 50 m from glacier on small moraine.  50 m from river.  Moraine fairly stable.
On glacier side of 1900 moraine (near the end of the lake). C. 50 from "beach" at end of lake. Moraine stable and fairly well covered with veg.
Near summit, c 100 m glacier side of bridge over main river, on second saw-toothed moraine inside terminal moraine.  On left hand side of foreland (looking towards the glacier). Stable moraine
On terminal moraine - ridge just before round pool on path.  5 m from path.
On path home c 50 m from river (on stretch of path going from ridge to foreland). Site very close to very large boulder.
Close to snout, around 10 m from left hand side of snout and around 100 m above pool where river leaves glacier.  Below unofficial path , glacier tongues on backwall in full view.
Around 50 m down from site 1.  c. 15 m from pool in front of glacier and 25 m from glacier snout.  On young unstable moraines.
On moraine below "post-box" at end of official path.  Halfway down the slope between post-box and river.
30 m away from site 3 (away from camp and slightly lower on slope).

On first moraine below large rock outcrop on which letterbox stands, c. 60 m to right of path (looking towards terminal moraine) and 100 m from river.  Here river divides into 2.  Further right 2 large meltwater streams flow down valley wall.
c. 30 m along from site 5 on same ridge towards meltwater streams.

On moraine summit.  Moraine halfway down foreland and behind three massive boulders (just after crossing two large meltwater streams).  C. 50 m from path and between meltwater stream on one valley wall and debris flow on far valley wall.
30 m away from site 7, towards meltwater stream on ridge slightly behind it but part of same complex.

On first ridge of a complex of moraines, two thirds of the way back across the foreland.  Beyond flat sandur c. 100 m from river and 60 m from where path crosses moraine.  Opposite meltwater stream on far valley wall.
On same ridge as site 9 but on other side of path. C. 50 m from site 9, 15 m from path and 20 m from river.  Here river very dissected.  Near crest of low stable moraine.
On low continuous moraine halfway between sites 9 and 10 and terminal moraine. C. 50 m from the path and 60 m from the river.  Opposite large meltwater stream running down opposite valley wall.
c. 20 m away from site 11 on same ridge (away from river). Near summit of ridge.
Above former fireplace.  On terminal moraine near the crest, c. 20 m from path to the left (looking towards terminal moraine).
On terminal moraine c. 15 m to right of path (looking towards terminal moraine). Near moraine crest.
Below base of 1930 moraine. Halfway between 1930 and terminal moraine, on right of foreland.
Just outside terminal moraine, directly behind site 14. In field grazed by sheep. Quite bouldery.
Just outside terminal moraine in grazed field. C 30 m from river and 30 m from path.
In field c. 150 m from terminal moraine and 50 m from path to right of glacier foreland (looking towards village). Site close to nearly last of large boulders scattered in field i.e. nearest village.

c. 50 m to the right of site 17 (looking towards village) and c. 200 m from the terminal moraine.  Halfway between site 17 and fern covered valley wall. In scattered large boulders in field - probably grazed.
c 50 m from the glacier snout and c 10 m from large snowpatch in front of it. C 30 from main meltwater river.
c. 200 m beyond site 4 and 50 m from stream.  Close to large triangular boulder.
1930/1940 moraine - first clear moraine on foreland. C 100 m from the river.  On fairly stable, well vegetated moraine.
On moraine two thirds of the way across the foreland, beyond large open area, c 4 m above the path and 10 m from the river.  Stable, well vegetated moraine. Near moraine summit.
Site on terminal moraine, approx 25 m to left of path (towards glacier).  Just behind a very large squarish boulder, in fairly dense birch woodland.

Near large blocky boulders, 50 m to right of path.  Outside terminal moraine on right hand side of foreland (looking to glacier). In fairly boggy area c 150 m beyond terminal moraine and 25 m from path.
At the snout c 30 m to the river and c. 50 m to the glacier.
On large moraine beyond 1750, behind site 10.  Veg. distinct band of Juniperus and Salix on moraine.
Around a third of the way down the foreland on rock-ledge, nearly at break of slope, half way down foreland and 500 m from snout.
On moraine in thick Betula woodland, c 50 m from path and 150 m from bottom of rock ledge.
On inner part of terminal moraine complex c. 20m from path on a level with farmhouse. Stable, fairly well-defined moraine
Outside Tuftbreen terminal moraine, towards Bergsetbreen, after second wooden bridge. 3 m from stream and 50 m from main path on side path in thick Betula woodland.
c. 50 m from the extreme right hand side of glacier.  Surroundings mainly bare rock and till with patches of Oxyria, Saxifrages, grasses and sedges
On terminal moraine just after it crosses stream i.e. on left of foreland (looking towards glacier). C 20 m from the stream, close to where stream forks.
Opposite jetty on the lake on the slope - moraine contains abundant fines.  Veg= shrubs of Betula and Salix spp.  L. corniculatus abundant, Dryopteris present - poss. site of late snowlie

c. 50 m above the path marked with t s c100 m to stream nearest car park on glacier side.  Glacier side of first main outcrop.  Mainly rock outcrops with patches of dense Betula-Salix scrub between. Close to rock outcrop covered in slime.
JAM quadrat 374 c. 50 m to left of Storbreen 5  (looking towards the glacier)

1875 moraine between campsite and end of lake within view of gauging station on other side of river.  Just before river divides c.50 m from edge of river.  Site on slope facing glacier.  Moraine fairly stable.  On moraine stunted birch and Salix and Ericaceae abundant while between moraines very dense Betula pubescens woodland.
On 1860 (?) behind the campsite c 100m from river on slope facing glacier.  Again Ericaceae-Betula scrub
Close to top of 1840 (?) moraine, c. half-way between 1860 and 1750.  Also site half-way between road and river.  Veg. dominated by Betula and Ericaceae.

On outmost moraine, beyond toll-booth on opposite side of road, on glacier side.  Half-way between top of moraine and pond at bottom.  Betulas much larger and some Salix.  Understorey dominated by Vaccinium rather than Calluna and Empetrum.  Less moss because forest floor covered in thick leaf litter but boulders covered in moss.
On outer side of terminal moraine on Mjolk road behind pit, behind outhouse in dense Betula woodland above bank behind road.  Thick Betula woodland and ground layer various Ericaceae.
In Betula copse between river and campsite, opposite bridge.  On opposite side of road is small hut.  Veg - thick Betula woodland with Ericaceous ground layer.
c. 30 m from the snout, between two meltwater streams. On a slight ridge.
On 1930 moraine - at end of flat area in front of snout.  Slightly to the right of foreland (looking towards glacier).
Just in front of lake in front of glacier on a small spur into the lake.  C. 50 m from the glacier itself.  Close to where river leaves the lake.

Around a third of the way back from the snout, nearly at the end of the level in front of snout and close to where slope gets steeper and waterfall, c. 10 m from river.  On a level with small meltwater stream on opposite valley wall.
Two thirds of the way back from snout, level with halfway down waterfall. C. 50 m from river.  On a level with third meltwater stream on opposite valley wall.
On terminal moraine, 60 m beyond National Park sign.

c. 200m beyond terminal moraine, on first large ridge outside terminal moraine near large black boulder. C. 25 m above path and 60 m above river. C. halfway along scree slope on opposite side of valley.

c. 30 m from the glacier snout and c. 5 m from the meltwater stream nearest the snout.  Large unstable fresh moraines. Veg mostly clumps of Poa , moss and small plants of Oxyria and Cerastium in hollows in moraine.

150 m behind 2.  Now on more stable, better vegetated moraine.  Beginning of Salix zone including S. glauca and Salix herbacea.  Clumps of Poa and Oxyria much bigger.  Cerastium still present but many plants look sickly.  This site above a flush site.
On large stable moraine c.150 m behind site 3.  Next to large boulder marked P2 and 1979.  Moraine sparsely vegetated.  Substrate - thick clayey layer and occasional large boulders.
1930 moraine - large stable moraine.  Veg mainly moss, lichens and Poa.  Between two large melt-water streams.
On 1750 moraine, where 1750 moraine forms large mound going towards lake.  Veg - Salix glauca and Ericaceae.
On "terminal moraine" - complex series of heavily dissected pre LIA moraines.  Near top of moraine facing glacier.  Veg. - mostly Juncus and Vaccinium v.i.
Outside of terminal moraine complex, facing away from the glacier and towards river.  Veg Juncus and Ericaceae.
Site on ridge just above river, close to cairn, on slope facing glacier.  Veg. - closed heath of Ericaceous spp.

c. 20 m from the glacier snout close to where the meltwater stream leaves it. C. 10 m from main meltwater stream. C. 20 m below the path on the left hand side of meltwater stream (looking towards glacier). Below small rock outcrop.
Just beyond where path crosses main meltwater stream (i.e. lake side). C. 50 m above path on a small ridge.  Near the crest of the ridge c. 20 m above stream on rockbar.
On 1930? Moraine, c 30 above the river.

c. 200 m below site 3.  On low ridge close to meltwater stream halfway between site 3 and 1930 moraine. C. 10 above side meltwater stream and on a level with where the main meltwater stream runs down the valley.
On 1930 moraine c. 15 m from where stream cuts through moraine.  Near the crest of moraine. Close to large area of standing water where water from small lake flows into main river.

On 1750 moraine.  C. 50 m from path close to where path bends round to lake.
Just outside the terminal moraine, c. 25 m below path, amongst rock outcrops

c. 30 m from the glacier snout, 150 m from where stream leaves the lake. C 100 m to left of large painted cairn (looking towards glacier).
Third of the way down foreland near break of slope, c. 15 m from river, fairly close to path.
c. 100 m from river and 50 m from path, near bottom of steep slope on small moraine.  Around two thirds of the way down the foreland.
On terminal moraine, c. 70 m above the path, on moraine summit.
On first ridge outside terminal moraine, near large back lichen-covered boulder.  Very exposed.
c. 10 m from the snout/front of snowpatch and c 15 m from the main meltwater stream (on a ridge above it). Substrate - ridge of bare rock.  Small pockets of veg.  Very exposed.

Two thirds of the way down foreland, past where river divides for the second time and near rapids.  C 100m above river on large complex moraine, on slope facing glacier.  Fairly stable.
On flat area beyond foreland, near some large black-lichen covered boulders and some brown outcrops. 20 m glacier side of path and 20 m from a small lake.

Third of way down foreland, 10 m to right of "P" boulder and 20 m to right of main meltwater stream (looking at glacier).
Two thirds of way down foreland from snout, same side of stream as Silla 2, just before fairly prominent lateral ridge/moraine.
c. 100 m upslope from the river on terminal moraine..  Veg. mainly Carex, R. glacialis, S. herbacea etc.

c. 150 m above river on "shoulder" of ridges beyond the "terminal moraine". Veg. - variety of vegetation communities - S. herbacea, Empetrum, B. nana etc.  All in v. close proximity. Salix glauca close by.
Snout poorly defined because so much snow around.  Site as near to ice as possible.  Frequent outcrops of rock and moraines very unstable.  Veg. v. sparse.
200 m downslope of Hogvaglbreen 1 on stone stripes, c 7 m from river.  Veg. v. sparse
Near top of large moraine inside terminal moraine, downslope from last site and across river.  Moraine fairly stable, veg. still sparse.
On top of terminal moraine to right of last site (looking towards lake). Site c 200 m from lake - on a level with downstream end of lake..  Moraine stable.
Beyond terminal moraine, on spur between two lakes. Very close to very large boulder/rock outcrop - easily visible from terminal moraine.  C. 50 to lake.  V. stable.
50 m from glacier snout, 4-5 ridges back, between the 2 main meltwater streams.

c 20 m from snow/snout of glaciers.  Whole area dissected by numerous meltwater streams.  Site on a slight ridge near centre of glacier.  Area on a gentle slope and fairly stable.  Plenty of moss and also some R. glacialis, Poa and Oxyria.

On top of first large, well defined moraine around 100 m from the river, on the left hand side of foreland (looking towards glacier).Near summit and near cairn topped with red stone.  Moraine stable.  Veg. very complex.

On large moraine - just over the river where the slope of the river flattens and divides, on a level with second waterfall.  On right hand side of foreland, looking towards the glacier.  Third large moraine including terminal moraine.  Moraine stable but summit very arid.  Veg sparse.
On terminal moraine.  Two thirds across moraine on Leirvassbu side.  150 m to nearest branch of river.  Slightly upslope of cairn with red top near the river.
Away from foreland, just below path, close to huge black-lichen covered boulder - fairly close to top of ridge opposite terminal moraine.  Veg dominated by Juncus trifidus and Salix herbacea.
c. 20 m from the snout of glacier, c. 3 m from main melt-water stream.  Veg. v sparse and moraine very unstable.
c. 100 m from river on bare rockface - halfway down steepest slope.  Above pool.  Area mainly bare rock , veg and unstable soil between ledges.

On ridge slope facing glacier, at bottom of waterfall at end of gentle slope.  Close to where river divides for the second time, before steep drop to terminal moraine and other huge moraines at the end of the foreland.  C 200 m from river.  Beyond stream across foreland.
Close to gap in terminal moraine to left-hand of foreland (looking towards glacier). Close to rock marked with a cross.  Moraine huge but generally stable.  Closed veg cover.
V. close to 2 huge boulders in alpine meadow below terminal moraine.  Third of the way between terminal moraine and river.
c 75 m from the snout and 10 m from river.  Very open area of young, unstable, dissected moraines.
At break of slope on foreland, beyond where river divides and drops steeply.  10 m from river. 1930 moraine?
Two thirds of way down foreland on first complex of ridges before Svellnosbreen meltwater stream.  150 m above river
On 1750 terminal moraine, 200 m from river.  Near summit and end of moraine.
300 m outside terminal moraine, 10 m from river.  On ridge close to path.
c 30 m from the snout, c 10 m from main meltwater stream.
Third of way down Styggebreen foreland, 10 m from river and 20 m below path.  50 m above break of slope above rock ledge.
Coordinates estimated from Google Earth
notes: Lithology: sand

locationnotes: Two thirds of way down foreland - 150 m below base of the rockbar and 10 m from river.  Large, stable moraine.
On terminal/lateral moraine of Styggebreen, just at the birch treeline.  Several hundred m from river.
Around 300 m below terminal moraine in bouldery area in birch woodland.  On knoll between 2 river channels.
c 60 m from the snout and 20 m above the path on the left of the foreland looking at the glacier.  Unstable moraine.
On first large moraine going away from the snout.   A third of the way up lower slope.  Near large rounded boulder, prominent on the skyline.
On terminal moraine around 100 m above the path and 150 m from the river, c. a third of the way up the slope in a complex of moraines.
Around 200 m outside the terminal moraine, 10 m above the path and 30 m above the river.  On well vegetated ridge just above the break of slope.
10 m from snout on a rockbar.
On knoll 20 below main meltwater stream, on lower part of rock bar.
250 m below site 4, on first of 1930 ridges.
On second of 1930 s ridges, 50 m from main meltwater stream.
75 m along the moraine away from 1930 ridge.  Above a small permanent pool fringed by Eriophorum.
100 m from foot of 1930 ridge.
On moraine just inside terminal moraine, close to ridge summit.
On terminal moraine at the ridge summit.
Just outside the terminal moraine on the ridge top, close to JA Matthews C14 pit.
Near end and top of ridge 200 m behind site 16.  Open exposed site.
On last ridge, near large brown boulder, 100 m from meltwater stream.  Parallel to peak on right hand side (looking towards glacier).

On1930? Moraine, 1st ridge in the sequence leading to the terminal moraine beyond the sandur - c 20 m above the floodplain.  Moraine largely washed away by river. Near the summit of the moraine near very large boulder.
Near crest of terminal moraine, around 100 m from where river cuts through terminal moraine.  NB last of around 3 ridges beyond sandur.  Fairly close to centre of terminal moraine.
Approx 100 m outside terminal moraine.  Outside two streams.  On ridge roughly parallel to outermost tip of terminal moraine, 100 m away.
c. 30 m to glacier snout and slightly to right of foreland (looking towards glacier). Near end of second large medial moraine from right.
c. 15 m to left of site 1, slightly higher on medial moraine ridge.
On next large ridge, 200 m from glacier snout.
c. 15 m away, higher on same ridge.
On next but one ridge. Near top of steep slope before ground levels out towards snout.
c. 20 m above site 5.
On next ridge, halfway down steep slope facing glacier. Halfway down foreland.
Close to top of same ridge.
At foot of steep slope close to very small pool (15 m away).  30 m from foot of snowpatch, fairly flat.
Crest of same ridge.  Can see Grjotbreen B lake.
One ridge in from terminal moraine
Same ridge, nearer glacier.
On terminal moraine, within sight of Grjotbreen B terminal moraine and river.  Close to centre of foreland.
25 m to the left of site 13.
Just outside the terminal moraine below snowpatch.  Beyond boulders beneath which runs stream.  Towards river.
10 m closer to river, just outside terminal moraine.
On ridge between snowpatch below terminal moraine and river.  First ridge after terminal moraine.
c. 15 m closer to river than site 17.
20 m from the front of snow at foot of first ridge, half way along glacier snout.  Hut in view from here
Near the top of the ridge.  50 m above site 2.  Loose angular boulders.
On next moraine, on crest.
On same moraine, towards Grjotbreen, where it divides, nearest terminal moraine.
On next continuous ridge, halfway up ridge - 1-2 ridges in from terminal moraine.
On first ridge behind site 10, towards Grjotbreen (ridge just inside terminal moraine).
On terminal moraine, towards Veobreen.
Just outside terminal moraine, 10 m above snowpatch.  Above large boulder below snowpatch
Outside terminal moraine, just beyond snowpatch, very close to large boulder below snowpatch.  Just beyond snow/stone stripe boundary.  Close to narrowest part of snowpatch.
c. 30 m from the snout slightly to the right of the foreland and 10 m above river
c. 60 m from snout slightly to right of foreland.  Substrate is large bare unstable boulders
Two thirds of the way across foreland.
On terminal moraine, within sight of the river.  On highest part of moraine
100 m outside terminal moraine, to left of large snowpatch.

vegdescription: The flat shores of the lake are surrounded by Betula, Picea, and Pinus with scattered stands of Ulmus, Tilia, Alnus and Quercus. Catchment is predominantly forested but also partly covered by fields.
Stand-scale site situated under a closed canopy of Betula, Picea and Pinus.
notes: Sample type: peat/soil

vegdescription: Lake surrounded by scattered stands of Alnus incana/glutinosa, Betula pendula/pubescens, Picea abies, Pinus sylvestris and Quercus robur. Landscape is predominantly open fields and meadows.
Lake is surrounded by open fields and scarce stands of pine (Pinus sylvestris) and birch (Betula pubescens).

The surrounding landscape comprises a mixture of cultivated land and pasture overlaying sandy and podzolic soils. The modern vegetation cover along the lake margins comprises Alnus incana/glutinosa, Betula pendula/pubescens, Picea abies, Pinus sylvestris, Quercus robur.
The lake s catchment area is covered by pine forest and bogs.
Pine, spruce and birch are dominant tree species.
notes: Sample type: peat/soil

vegdescription: The small catchment consists of the steep slopes of a volcanic crater which forms the site. At present, the slopes are covered by thin soils and vegetation - grasses, shrubs with occasional stands of juniper and dwarf birch. In some areas, the deep erosion spots reveal bare rock.
Lake is located in the forest. Vegetation: dominates by pine, secondary spruce and birch

vegdescription: near beach forest with groups of Ostrya carpinifolia, Betula pendula and artificial plantation of Pinus sylvestris
mixed coniferous-deciduous forest, Picea abies (35%), Pinus sylvestris (35%), Abies alba (15%), single trees of Betula pendula, Salix sp/, Alnus glutinosa, Fagus sylvatica.
mixed coniferous forest, Picea abies (45%), Pinus sylvestris (45%), single trees of Abies alba, undergrowth of vaccinium myrtillus
subalpine belt, herbaceous vegetation with scattered groups of Pinus mugo

Mixed coniferous community of Picea abies. The proportions of the main tree species near the sampling site were Picea abies (30 %), Pinus peuce Griesb. (19 %) and P. mugo Turra (51 %). Single trees of P. sylvestris L. and Betula pendula Roth were also found.
Coniferous community of Picea abies (97 %), with some admixture of Abies alba (3 %).
Mixed coniferous community, composed of Picea abies (72 %) and Abies alba (28 %). Single trees of Salix caprea L. were also present.
